{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fa18099b-b342-483c-b0e2-00518eee2326","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update, since workload manifests and packs may be out of sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads that are already recorded as installed but have corrupted or missing files. It doesn't fetch newer versions.\n\nAfter updating, verify with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf `update` doesn't resolve it, try `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it installs any workloads declared in your project file or `global.json`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"10a6558d-5815-4a8b-bd97-ecae96ca83e5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any code.","outputTokens":244},"id":"29d8bb88-fc0b-4aa5-9507-6fab857ed4b3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:41:51.351Z","parentId":"1d54aa02-259b-4168-bd42-51a353cf1650"}
